# @targon・4  Targon v4 is released!

## Validator update steps
- Ensure docker and nvidia smi / cuda are installed on your server.
- Minimum requirement 80gb VRAM (a100)
- Pull down latest code
- Decide what models / method
   - Validators can either choose their own models or mimic the mainfold validator. see readme for more info
   - https://github.com/manifold-inc/targon?tab=readme-ov-file#running-a-validator
- Start your validator (see readme for required and optional arguments)
## Miners
- Fill in code for GET and POST model functions
  - receive_models
  - list_models
 - implement reverse proxy to different models
   - This is up to the miner on how they wish to do this. Miners can use the `X-Targon-Model` to route requests to multiple miner instances, or do it in the base miner code. 

Please reach out with questions or issues. We will be closely monitoring as this is a very large and complex update.

Also note, stats will be down for a bit during the update due to new fields and data formats.

what's the difference between honest and WC?

An honest validator actually runs the validation code for the subnet, ranks the miners, and sets weights based on the performance of the miners.
Weight copiers just watch the weights set by other (honest) validators and copy them (either following just one validator, some composite mechanism, whatever) and don't actually run any servers/do any work.
Weight copiers are essentially just stealing money in my opinion, because they get paid, often times quite a bit, for doing nothing and contributing nothing to the network.  They could even do the child hotkey thing at this point.  What's particularly egregious is when a weight copier sets 0% root weight on a subnet and "validates" anyways, meaning they block their weights' share of emissions from going to the subnet whilst still getting paid for "validating".  Pretty gross stuff.

Logprobs are an exceptionally good way to verify outputs.  There's really no possible way to generate a "ground truth" document because of hardware/software differences and (random) order of operations on some things due to non-deterministic optimizations and such.  Logprobs are the closest thing we can really get, but it was missing a few useful checks.

The issue is that vllm, when running inference, automatically adds `"add_generation_prompt": True` when performing the `tokenizer.apply_chat_template(..)` call, whereas the verifier doesn't have this flag.  The confounding factor is that the llama-8b instruct model actually doesn't need to explicitly set that flag, but the other models do (for chat endpoints specifically).  So the fix is quite simple, just need `add_generation_prompt=True` in the verifier code when calling `apply_chat_template`
The flag basically just adds a suffix to the prompt to trigger the mode to generate as the assistant role, e.g.:
```python
>>> from transformers import AutoTokenizer
>>> tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('NTQAI/Nxcode-CQ-7B-orpo')
>>> tokenizer.apply_chat_template([{"role": "system", "content": "You are Bob."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Hi Bob."}], tokenize=False)
'<|im_start|>system\nYou are Bob.<|im_end|>\n<|im_start|>user\nHi Bob.<|im_end|>\n'
>>> tokenizer.apply_chat_template([{"role": "system", "content": "You are Bob."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Hi Bob."}], tokenize=False, add_generation_prompt=True)
'<|im_start|>system\nYou are Bob.<|im_end|>\n<|im_start|>user\nHi Bob.<|im_end|>\n<|im_start|>assistant\n'
```
So really it's just that vllm chat endpoints automatically add `<|im_start|>assistant\n` and the verifier doesn't for all models.
